The special value of these extracts from Gascoigne’s Manu· script resides in the fact, that they are singularly illustrative of the darkest period in the social and political history of England. Other contemporary materials are, first, the Rolls os Parliament‚ which have never been sufficiently examined; next, the dry Chronicle os Wyrcestre; next, the pedantic dissertations ol Whetehamstede; and lastly, the Paston Letters. For the rest, the student os history must rely on the narratives os the Tudor annalists. ln Gascoigne we have an estimate of English society, made by a contemporary who had considerable opp portunities for forming a judgment, and possessed sufficient fearlessness in dealing with men and facts. His words may sometimes seem to be those os a disappointed man, osten of an angry man; but os his genuine piety, and sincere desire for the reformation of society, there can be no doubt.
